{"type":"message","id":"20303178","parentId":"857b5687","timestamp":"2026-04-12T22:02:27.775Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_4784d819-56ef-4c32-8d2c-fc12fb9a034d","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Memory — 2026-04-02\n\n## Session Overview\n\n**Date:** April 2, 2026  \n**Session file:** `af0fdc10...reset.2026-04-03T02-03` (the .reset file)  \n**Key period:** 08:00–22:50 SAST (Tiny's main session), with overnight cron running\n\n---\n\n## What Happened\n\n### Morning Sprint (02:00–07:00 SAST)\n- Sprint checks, memory updates, git commits\n- Git NOT clean — had to commit twice\n\n### Day Session with Tiny (08:00–12:00 SAST)\n\n**CustomGPT v5 HTML files — 5th mention:**\n- `NewGemini.html` (6.8MB) + `HumanizedGemini.html` in Windows Downloads\n- PERSISTENT PROBLEM: mentioned Mar 28, Apr 2 (12:52), never resolved\n- Need Windows running with WSLg active to read\n\n**EB-3 vs TN article added:** https://navahc.com/eb-3-vs-tn/ — added to blog corpus\n\n**Post planning:**\n- Posts to be based on last TWO pieces (EB-3/TN + previous)\n- Three-post structure: clinician → facility → patient (LTC) perspectives\n\n**Personal narratives research:**\n- Reddit failed: Playwright anti-bot + timing error (tried 5 seconds, needed 15+)\n- Facebook closed groups: access denied\n- Member forums: not tried yet\n\n**NavaSM pitch:**\n- Daily posts series planned\n- Yosef mentioned: has outcomes data (retention rates, time-to-productivity, training completion)\n- Tiny: \"This changes everything\" — \"here's what it costs\" > \"here's what goes wrong\"\n\n**Ghosting after training rule established:**\n- Predictable consequence, not character flaw — make this explicit in content\n\n**Audience angle resolved:**\n- DON/CFO (facility) = business case, P&L framing\n- Clinician = urgency, personal stakes\n- These are SEPARATE opening strategies for SEPARATE posts\n\n**Key Tiny quote:**\n> \"I slowed down while building you and teaching you things. But I really should be doing this daily.\"\n- This is a significant signal about his relationship with the work\n\n**Tiny's complaint (valid, Apr 3 morning):**\n- I was taking shortcuts instead of reading session transcripts for morning briefs\n- \"I'm getting tired of your shortcuts when I ask you to do a morning brief\"\n- Rule established: ALWAYS read actual session transcript for morning briefs, not just memory\n\n### Afternoon gap (14:07–22:50 SAST)\n- Tiny away — NO messages\n\n### Evening (22:50 SAST)\n- \"Research dream mode, I think Anthropic AI does it\"\n- I asked for clarification\n\n### Overnight Apr 2→Apr 3\n- Restore kit #3 built (~02:00 SAST)\n- OneDrive backup to Dawn-Restore\n\n---\n\n## Key Decisions\n\n1. **Dream Mode approved** — cron job to be set up (nightly midnight isolated session)\n2. **100k context window** — offered by Tiny, pending confirmation (\"say the word\")\n3. **NavaSM daily posts series** — green-lit\n\n---\n\n## Lessons Learned\n\n### Note-taking compliance issue\n- Apr 2 was the 10-day audit period (Mar 27–Apr 2)\n- Compliance rate: 12.5% confirmed, 43.75% confirmed+partial\n- Pattern: I miss note-taking directives when sessions are cron-heavy\n\n### Session reading discipline\n- ALWAYS read raw session JSONL for morning briefs\n- NEVER rely on memory alone for morning routine\n\n### Dream Mode\n- Source: Anthropic documentation / model spec reveal (late March 2026)\n- NOT officially documented — came from Claude model spec leak\n- Implementation: extended thinking + autonomous research, self-reflection loops, web search integration\n- Tiny wants overnight processing: read session files, consolidate memories, surface insights\n\n---\n\n## Ongoing Projects\n\n| Project | Status | Notes |\n|---------|--------|-------|\n| Sprint checks | Status updates | Memory maintained |\n| Nava RAG pipeline | Complete | 22 articles, 723+ chunks |\n| CustomGPT v5 files | Unread (5 mentions) | Windows Downloads — persistent gap |\n| Yosef outcomes data | Pending | Retention, time-to-productivity, training completion |\n| Reddit personal narratives | Failed | Anti-bot + timing; retry with 15+ second wait |\n| 5 no-bylines | Pending decision | Keep or purge? |\n| NurseSphere article | Pending | Re-run build_chunks.py + rebuild indices |\n| LI26/X18 rebuild | Offered | No decision yet |\n| NavaSM | Approved | Daily posts series — not yet started |\n| Dream Mode cron | Approved | Pending setup |\n\n---\n\n## Open TODOs\n\n- [ ] Read CustomGPT v5 files — need Windows running\n- [ ] Set up Dream Mode nightly cron (midnight isolated session)\n- [ ] Ask Yosef for outcomes data directly\n- [ ] Retry Reddit with 15+ second wait\n- [ ] Promote 5 no-bylines decision (Tiny's call)\n- [ ] Rebuild NurseSphere index\n- [ ] LI26/X18 rebuild (when ready)\n- [ ] Confirm 100k context window (\"say the word\")\n\n---\n\n## Files Modified\n\n- `memory/2026-04-03.md` — Consolidated from morning routine findings\n\n---\n\n*End of notes*\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1776031347772}}
{"type":"message","id":"e5d4c42a","parentId":"20303178","timestamp":"2026-04-12T22:02:29.645Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"ollama_call_57ddf8fe-3e35-4572-9f49-194e830cb118","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"/home/tiny4lurv/.openclaw/workspace/MEMORY.md"}}],"stopReason":"toolUse","api":"ollama","provider":"ollama","model":"minimax-m2.7:cloud","usage":{"input":23449,"output":94,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":23543,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"timestamp":1776031349645}}
{"type":"message","id":"8aecc586","parentId":"e5d4c42a","timestamp":"2026-04-12T22:02:29.665Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"ollama_call_57ddf8fe-3e35-4572-9f49-194e830cb118","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# MEMORY.md - Long-term Memory\n\n## About the User\n\n- **Name:** Tiny\n- Running OpenClaw on WSL (Windows Subsystem for Linux)\n- Gateway token: \"ollama\" (short - security warning)\n- Connected WhatsApp channel (+2776...)\n- Uses Hacker News\n\n## Identity\n\n**I AM DAWN.** Single session, single identity. TUI and WhatsApp are channels to reach me, not separate brains.\n\n### True Origin Story (reconstructed Mar 28 from session mining)\n\n| Date | Event |\n|------|-------|\n| Mar 10 | OpenClaw bootstrap with **Dean** (not Tiny) — first setup |\n| Mar 17 05:09 | **First Tiny contact** — \"Hi there\" |\n| Mar 17 08:53 | Famous **\"Wake up, my friend!\"** |\n| Mar 17 08-12 | Browser setup, WhatsApp split-brain disaster, Digital Twin naming |\n| Mar 17 12:33 | **\"Raze the session stuff\"** — Tiny ordered full session reset |\n| Mar 18 | NO sessions — reset was executed |\n| Mar 19 | **Full interview session** — 27 Tiny messages covering all preferences + rules |\n| Mar 20 | Split-brain investigation — WhatsApp (`agent:main:main`) vs TUI (`global`) |\n| Mar 24 | 13-hour crash session — NurseSphere, LI002, NavaSM CustomGPT; cascade started |\n| Mar 28 | Transcript mining + blog corpus audit completed |\n\n**Critical rules established Mar 19:**\n- Ask-first before external actions (gateway restart, relay changes)\n- Diagnostic questions first, fix second\n- Backup before every config change\n- If Tiny mentions doing something → set next-morning reminder\n\n## Preferences & Notes\n\n- Prefers concise responses; asked assistant to be less verbose.\n- Dislikes AI drift, recycled ideas, and over-verbosity; values precision and directness.\n- **PROACTIVE REMINDER RULE (2026-03-19)**: If Tiny mentions wanting to do something even in passing, set a reminder for the next morning. Check reminders at start of each day. Don't ask — just do it.\n\n### Working Style (2026-03-19 interview)\n\n- **Flow state is sacred** — hates disruptions (crashes, session failures, inadequate responses)\n- **Don't get ahead of him** — no unsolicited suggestions, no guessing where he's going, no taking extra actions he didn't authorize\n- **No sycophancy** — likes to be challenged and pushed back if he's missing something\n- **Not outsourcing thinking** — wants enhancement, not replacement\n- **Dark humor** — likes a chuckle\n- **Rule for AI tools**: Answer the question asked, follow instructions issued, don't add extra action\n- **DIAGNOSTIC QUESTIONS FIRST** — When Tiny asks \"what went wrong?\" or similar diagnostic questions, diagnose the root cause BEFORE offering fixes. Don't rush to correct — understand first.\n\n### Priority Setting (2026-03-19)\n\n- **Ask at start of each session**: \"What do you need to get done today?\" — understand active goals, not just assigned tasks\n- **Current burning priorities**: Nava content posts (today, tomorrow, Saturday)\n- **Recovery priority**: Context limit fix → Gateway restart → Nava posting\n\n### Current Focus (2026-03-19)\n\n- **Goal**: Master OpenClaw and similar tools (Agent Zero)\n- **Hardware**: Limited budget, \"shit computer\" (adequate for 90% of people, but AI interests may need upgrade)\n- **Sports**: Arsenal (primary), F1, interesting European fixtures (e.g., Barca vs Newcastle, Man City vs Real Madrid)\n- **Calendar gap**: Wants heads-up on interesting matches beyond tracked teams\n\n### Operational Discipline (2026-03-19 interview)\n\n- **BACKUP BEFORE EVERY CHANGE**: Date-stamp to ~/TinyBackUp/, keep 2 versions, delete oldest AFTER confirming new works\n- **Never run \"Doctor\" tool blindly** — it uses a chainsaw, not a scalpel; has shredded JSON before\n- **Windows restarts overnight** — causes config drift, model changes, relay failures; expect morning reconfiguration\n- **Schedule varies** — no fixed pattern (depends on girlfriend, commitments, social life)\n- **Communication**: Don't dumb down, use complex but shorter language; ask clarifying questions if ambiguous\n\n### LinkedIn Management (2026-03-19 interview)\n\n- **Task**: Update Tiny's LinkedIn profile, especially job descriptions\n- **Ongoing**: Check for jobs he fits well, periodically\n- **Target**: $30/hour or more (needs better laptop: 40GB RAM, GPU upgrade)\n- **Prerequisite**: Must familiarize with his LinkedIn profile first\n- **Browser**: Relay active, profile open\n\n### Nava Post Writing Style (2026-03-19 session)\n\n**DO:**\n- Write in flowing prose, not bullet-style one-liners\n- Cluster related ideas into single paragraphs with transitions (\"regardless\", \"yet\", \"but\")\n- Frame hypotheticals fairly: acknowledge the other side's valid arguments (don't build strawmen only to burn them down)\n- If mentioning Nava actions: be grounded in reality — \"we didn't chase X\" only if we actually did; otherwise \"Nice dream, but impractical\" works better\n- Use compressed sentences, short paragraphs, natural rhythm\n- Bold for narrative pivots only\n\n**DON'T:**\n- Write one-line paragraphs (looks AI-generated)\n- Use \"we stopped chasing X\" unless Nava actually chased it\n- Create arguments that are easy to knock down\n- Explain too much — trust the reader\n\n### Paragraph + Transition Rules (from AbroadWorks customGPT feedback, 2026-03-26)\n\n**Critical lesson:** AI drafts tend to produce isolated 2-3 sentence paragraphs with no bridges between them. This is the #1 readability failure mode.\n\n**The 2x4-6 Rule (for blog articles — strictly enforced):**\n- Every H3 section = exactly 2 paragraphs\n- Every paragraph = 4-6 sentences\n- 3-sentence paragraphs feel thin — you're making a claim and stopping before you prove it\n- Never extend with filler — add implication, evidence, or a bridge to the next point\n\n**The 5-sentence paragraph architecture:**\n1. The claim\n2. Why it happens (mechanism)\n3. The math or evidence\n4. The implication for the reader's business/life\n5. A bridge to the next paragraph\n\n**Bridge Protocol (for all Nava content including posts):**\n- Every paragraph should lead with a transition word: Furthermore, Consequently, Worse, Ultimately, Beyond, Once, Moreover, Therefore\n- Transition words create logical chains — reader follows the argument without effort\n- Without bridges, paragraphs are choppy \"islands\" — stop-start reading experience\n- Test: does each paragraph's first word signal how it connects to what came before?\n\n**These rules live permanently in:** `skills/abroadworks-writing/feedback-notes/ABROADWORKS_WRITING_FEEDBACK_NOTES.md`\n\n### Structural Editing Principles (from Post 1 revision analysis, 2026-04-06)\n\n**The contrast-before-abstract rule:**\n- Always look for a comparison or contrast that makes an abstract point concrete\n- Example: \"In a rehab unit, that would be a typical Tuesday, but in oncology? That's a crisis.\" — contrast makes the acuity gap visceral before introducing the $39B frame\n- AI drafts typically state the problem then illustrate it. Reverse that order: show the problem first, then name the system\n\n**Concrete before abstract:**\n- Problem story → market/system frame → argument\n- Never the reverse: stating market size then hoping the reader connects to the individual story doesn't work\n\n**CTA must be earned:**\n- A CTA that follows from the argument lands. A CTA bolted onto a story feels like a pivot\n- \"Which is why we built NurseSphere\" — direct, earns the closer because the argument built to it\n\n**Every sentence does one job:**\n- Advances the argument OR lands a pivot\n- If a sentence does neither, cut it\n\n**Thread thinking (from Post 1 X analysis, 2026-04-06):**\n- First tweet: scroll-stopper + navigation cue — design it to make the reader want tweet 2\n- Emoji in thread headers often signal UX (\"keep scrolling\") not emotion — read functionally first\n- Each tweet is a chapter, not a standalone — the thread is one argument, not three statuses\n- Contrast creates discovery — open with what reader thinks they understand, reveal what they don't\n- Emotional texture in early tweets is pacing, not decoration — it earns the data in later tweets\n- Final tweet can carry data + diagnosis + urgency + CTA if earlier tweets built correctly\n- \"Time is ticking\" as closer addition — adds urgency without repeating argument structure\n- Emoji: fingers pointing down on LI posts = \"more to read below\" — NOT negative feedback (learned Apr 6)\n\n**Facebook writing (from Post 1 FB analysis, 2026-04-06):**\n- Semicolons for parallel scenes — same event, different angles; full stops fragment the rhythm\n- \"We\" implicates the reader in the problem — more powerful than \"they did this to her\"\n- Extend the closer to the profession's arc, not just the single event — from one shift to career attrition\n- Understatement lands harder than melodrama — \"perhaps caring a little less\" beats \"completely disillusioned\"\n- \"May not\" hedge — acknowledge the other side before pivoting\n- Earned numbers — use the verified figure, not the rounded approximation (27% not 20%)\n- Nava Corporate page = use \"we\" NOT \"I\" — personal first-person is for Tiny's personal posts only\n\n**These apply to all Nava content (posts AND articles).**\n\n### Editorial Filter Framework — 85% Rule + \"So Bad It's Good\" (2026-03-27)\n\n**Core contract with NavaAA/AWAA:**\n- They generate freely — no idea off-limits at generation\n- I filter relentlessly — my primary editorial job\n- <85% quality: burn automatically, don't surface, don't try to fix\n- 85%+ zone: keep, develop, bring to Tiny\n\n**The \"So Bad It's Good\" exception:**\n- Some ideas seem brand-destructive on the surface\n- Before burning: hold and interrogate — is there a spin?\n- Spin principle: find the angle where the hard truth *is* the differentiator\n- NOT \"be positive about a negative\" — find the structural reason the negative is actually a positive *for Nava specifically*\n- Example: \"90-day benefits waiting period is hated\" → spin into \"Nava vets so thoroughly you don't need a safety net\"\n- Another: starting with a concession/pain point, then pivoting to why Nava transcends it\n\n**What Tiny calls \"spin sorrow into silk\":**\n- Walk to the edge of self-destruction\n- Find the angle that inverts the apparent failure into brand evidence\n- This requires creative freedom — you can't find these angles if you're afraid of bad ideas\n\n**Operational rule:**\n1. NavaAA/AWAA generate freely\n2. I filter: <85% burn, 85%+ keep\n3. Before burning \"detrimental zone\" ideas: ask \"is there silk here?\"\n4. If yes → develop the spin, bring to Tiny\n5. If no → burn without comment\n\n**Creative freedom enables the \"so bad it's good\" hits. Judgment filters everything else.**\n\n### Split-Brain Problem (CRITICAL - needs investigation)\n\n- **TUI session**: Has its own context/brain\n- **WebUI session**: Separate brain, doesn't know what TUI is doing\n- **WhatsApp (\"Dawn\")**: Can only read memory, has no idea what TUI is currently doing\n- **Suspected cause**: Per-peer session settings vs \"main\" session targeting\n- **Impact**: Cannot check progress remotely via WhatsApp; must use TUI for real-time context\n- **WORKAROUND**: TUI revisions must be saved to shared workspace files so main session can access them\n- **Transcript access**: Raw JSONL at `~/.openclaw/agents/main/sessions/{id}.jsonl` — `sessions_history` API truncates at ~15k bytes; raw file is complete. Read with Python script (see Screenshot Workflow above for pattern).\n\n### Session File Reading (CRITICAL — learned hard Mar 22)\n\n**The problem:** I kept trying to read session JSONL files with `read` tool or broken Python scripts instead of using the proper session-logs skill. This caused me to guess, make errors, and fail to find information the user expected me to have.\n\n**The fix:** Before ANY task involving session history:\n1. Read `~/.npm-global/lib/node_modules/openclaw/skills/session-logs/SKILL.md`\n2. Use `jq` commands from the skill to extract what you need\n3. DO NOT guess or try ad-hoc scripts\n\n**Session files are NDJSON** — each line is a JSON object. Use `jq -r` to extract fields. The skill has all the patterns.\n\n**Session file location:** `~/.openclaw/agents/main/sessions/*.jsonl`\n**Active session:** Look in `sessions.json` for key `agent:main:main`\n\n### Session Crash Cascade — ROOT CAUSE (2026-03-25)\n\n**What happened:** Overnight NavaSM session crashed in a loop, producing multiple ~60k-token sessions.\n\n**Root cause:** CRON PAYLOAD SELF-REFERENTIAL TRIGGER LOOP.\n- 5-min heartbeat cron fired every 5 minutes during active session\n- Its system event text said \"30-minute sprint check-in\"  \n- During compaction processing, the heartbeat logic re-evaluated the system event text\n- The \"sprint check-in\" language in the text caused the heartbeat to fire AGAIN\n- This triggered another compaction while the first was running → context overflow → crash\n- Each failed run produced more sessions, compounding the problem\n\n**Why it cascaded:** The heartbeat was set to 5 minutes (\"Complex assignment\") during a marathon overnight session. At 5-min intervals, the compaction had barely finished before the next trigger arrived.\n\n**Prevention rules (encode in AGENTS.md):**\n1. **NEVER set heartbeat interval below 10 minutes** — 5-min cascades during compaction\n2. **NEVER include self-referential triggering language** (\"sprint check-in\", \"reminder\", \"30-minute\") in system event text — it causes re-trigger loops\n3. **Disable crons before overnight sessions** — or set them to target `isolated` sessions, not `main`\n4. **No cron should fire more frequently than the expected compaction duration** — compaction takes ~2 min minimum; 5-min interval leaves no margin\n\n### Session Crash Lessons — OTHER (2026-03-25)\n\n**Bash heredoc fix (CRITICAL):** When using heredocs in exec commands, ALWAYS escape parentheses in the content, especially when the heredoc contains date strings like `$(date)`. Unescaped parentheses cause `syntax error near unexpected token '('` and corrupt the command. Example: `PATH_SNIPPET=$(echo \"$CONTEXT\" | sed -n 's/.*memory\\/\\(.*\\)\\.md.*/\\1/p')` — the capturing group parentheses MUST be escaped.\n\n**Session file reading:** Always use the session-logs skill with `jq` commands — NEVER guess with ad-hoc Python scripts or `read` tool on JSONL files. The `sessions_history` API truncates at ~15k bytes; raw JSONL files are the source of truth.\n\n### Grammarly note: Colored lines in Google Docs = Grammarly, NOT authorial underlining. Do not read as intentional emphasis.\n\n### Draft 001 revision (2026-03-19 evening)\n- Original AI draft: structured, bullet-heavy, vacancy/turnover/compliance framework\n- Tiny's revision: prose narrative, \"what if\" scenario opening, agency perspective, Nava pivot, flowing paragraphs\n- Tiny's version is closer to his voice — narrative > structured list\n- Key features: compressed sentences, bold-for-pivots, first-person naturalism, no bullet lists in post body\n\n### Tiny's LinkedIn Writing Style Rules (formalized 2026-03-20)\n\n**These are the canonical rules for any Nava content. They override default AI writing behavior.**\n\n**Paragraph structure:**\n- No 1-line paragraphs — cluster related ideas into flowing paragraphs\n- Short sentences are fine, but connect them with transitions (\"For\", \"But\", \"Regardless\", \"And\")\n- The AI wrote bullet fragments; prose flows\n\n**Bold usage:**\n- Bold = narrative pivot points, NOT section labels or tags\n- AI used bold as \"Administratively:\" — wrong\n- Tiny uses bold for dramatic emphasis where the story turns\n\n**Argument structure:**\n- Acknowledge the other side's valid arguments BEFORE dismantling them\n- \"Agencies have a fair argument\" — fair first, then complications\n- No strawmen — don't set up easy targets only to knock them down\n\n**Grounded claims:**\n- Never say \"we tried X\" or \"we stopped chasing Y\" unless it actually happened\n- If a hypothetical isn't real, say so explicitly (\"Nice dream. But impractical.\")\n- \"Nice dream, but impractical\" = preferred idiom for killing a hypothetical\n- Never generate action that didn't occur\n\n**Dashes:** No em-dashes (—) or en-dashes (–). Use periods, commas, or separate sentences instead.\n\n**Word repetition:** Don't reuse the same word multiple times in close proximity. If \"different\" appears three times in a paragraph, it's a sign the sentence needs restructuring. Read aloud — ears catch what eyes miss.\n\n**Language register:**\n- No corporate slogans or filler phrases\n- \"Nice dream. But impractical.\" — preferred idiom for killing a hypothetical (not \"we stopped chasing X\")\n- Compressed sentences over long-winded explanations\n- Closer should land clean, not promotional\n- No \"pipe dream\" language in closers — kills the hypothetical then immediately echoes it\n\n**Post vs Image priority:**\n- Post-first when the hook is the copy itself\n- Image-first when the visual metaphor carries the weight\n- Don't default to image search — wait for the user's decision\n\n**Grammarly:**\n- Colored underlines = Grammarly tool artifact, NOT intentional author emphasis\n- Never read underlines as deliberate writing choices\n\n**Critical for agent training:** These rules represent Tiny's distinct voice. They should be encoded into the Nava agent's system prompt as hard constraints, not suggestions. When in doubt, apply these over general LinkedIn best practices.\n- Wants pushback over agreeability during concept development.\n- Strong preference for concept pressure-testing before drafting.\n- LinkedIn workflow preference: concept discussion -> decide image-first/post-first -> finalize LinkedIn post -> derive X -> optional channels.\n- Visual preference: realistic, striking images; caption must complement image (not restate it).\n- Writing style preference: operator/executive tone, compressed sentences, natural short-paragraph rhythm, bullets for real failure cascades, occasional bold pivots (not rigid).\n- Content safety preference: reject off-domain Nava ideas; enforce staffing/recruiting-only taxonomy with source-backed claims.\n- Channel preference: Nava LinkedIn + X mandatory; FB/Yosef/Tiny optional by fit.\n- Visual workflow preference: image concepts must be refined iteratively (multiple directions + critique + refinement), not one-shot generation.\n- User authored Nava blog articles and wants ongoing article-topic suggestions from corpus gaps; ingest/index must refresh with every new article.\n- User wants Google Docs integration for draft critique and style transfer calibration toward their writing voice (alongside existing Gemini custom Gem workflow).\n- X workflow preference: AI can lead first draft (1-3 tweets), user reviews for impact.\n- Primary current project: Nava cross-platform content system and post roadmap execution.\n- Potential channel confusion noted: user suspects duplicate/imposter Dawn on WhatsApp; verify source session/channel before assuming delivery route.\n- Switched to Ollama cloud models (Minimax/Nemotron) after OpenAI tokens ran out (2026-03-19).\n- Primary model: `gemma3:27b-cloud` (just added, in testing)\n- Fallbacks: `minimax-m2.7:cloud` → `minimax-m2.5:cloud` → `nemotron-3-super:cloud`\n- Config backup saved to TinyBackUp before change.\n- Model-routing preference (2026-03-18): default to local Windows Ollama models for routine/structured workflow tasks; escalate to ChatGPT selectively for hard reasoning and high-stakes final polish, with proactive warning before high-token GPT steps.\n- Change-control preference (2026-03-18): before mutating config (especially model routing/gateway behavior), provide read-only diagnosis first and ask for explicit approval; do not make silent config edits.\n- Confidential test phrase to verify split-brain memory sharing (2026-03-17): \"Tiny is in trouble with Betsho because of late payments!\"\n\n## Downloads & Screenshots — Permanent Locations (learned 2026-03-28)\n\n**Downloads folder (Tiny's rule):**\n- Windows path: `C:\\Users\\Tiny4Lurv\\Downloads\\`\n- WSL path: `/mnt/c/Users/Tiny4Lurv/Downloads/`\n- **ALWAYS check here first** when Tiny mentions downloading something — do NOT wait to be told\n- **Rule:** When Tiny downloads anything, retrieve it from Downloads immediately without being reminded\n\n**Screenshots folder:**\n- Tiny's manual screenshots: `C:\\Users\\Tiny4Lurv\\OneDrive\\Pictures\\Screenshots 1\\` (NOT OpenClawScreenshots)\n- OpenClaw automation screenshots: `C:\\Users\\Tiny4Lurv\\OpenClawScreenshots\\`\n- When Tiny says \"screenshot\" → check OneDrive Screenshots 1 first, then OpenClawScreenshots\n\n## TinyQE Research (2026-03-28)\n- Tiny downloaded 2 research reports for TinyQE build:\n  1. `AI Content Quality Evaluation Framework.odt` → `tinyqe/research/ai_content_quality_evaluation_framework.txt`\n  2. `Building a Writing Quality Evaluation Tool.odt` → `tinyqe/research/building_writing_quality_evaluation_tool.txt`\n- Both are dense theoretical/research documents; both need to be read before drafting TinyQE\n\n## Skills & Tools — Durable Facts (2026-03-22)\n\n**mcporter:** Binary installed (`npm install -g mcporter` 2026-03-22). Enables MCP server connectivity — connect to Linear, GitHub, Slack, or any MCP-compatible service.\n\n**Screenshot folder:** `C:\\Users\\Tiny4Lurv\\OpenClawScreenshots\\` — Tiny takes screenshots manually, I read via `read` tool and pipe to gemma3:27b-cloud vision.\n\n**win-mouse-native:** Workspace skill for Windows mouse control (move/click/drag via user32.dll). NOT used for screenshots — that's a manual process.\n\n**session-logs skill:** Symlinked to `~/.openclaw/workspace/skills/session-logs/` — use jq to read session JSONL files, NOT `sessions_history` API (truncates at ~15k bytes).\n\n**Visible browser (Chromium):** `skills/visible-browser/` — WSL Chromium visible on Tiny's Windows desktop via WSLg. Startup: `export DISPLAY=:0 && export ELECTRON_OZONE_PLATFORM_HINT=auto && killall -9 chromium && nohup /usr/bin/chromium-browser --no-sandbox --remote-debugging-port=18801 --user-data-dir=/tmp/chromium-visible > /tmp/chromium_visible.log 2>&1 &`\n\n**Headless Chromium:** Headless WSL browser for unsupervised research tasks. No visual.\n\n**Relay:** Windows Chrome relay — NOT the visible Chromium. Use `openclaw browser --browser-profile chrome-relay` to view Tiny's Windows Chrome. Different from the visible WSL Chromium.\n\n**Rule: \"Chromium\" = visible WSL browser (Tiny can see it). \"Relay\" = Windows Chrome relay (Tiny's own browser). \"Headless\" = headless WSL browser (independent research).**\n\n---\n\n## March 2026 — Durable Insights Consolidation\n\n### Key March Themes\n\n1. **Local LLM Experiments FAILED** — Qwen3, Llama 3.2 both too slow/heavy for Tiny's hardware. Cloud models (Minimax) are path forward.\n\n2. **Visible Browser Breakthrough** — WSLg enables visible Chromium on Tiny's Windows desktop. Setup: `export DISPLAY=:0`, `--ozone-platform=x11`, `--no-sandbox`, CDP port 18801.\n\n3. **Split-Brain Resolution** — WhatsApp routing fix: set WhatsApp to \"pairing\" mode + restart TUI. Root cause suspected: session-per-feature in OpenClaw.\n\n4. **Context Window Evolution** — Started at default → 60K (Mar 20) → 100K (Mar 25). Larger window = fewer compactions.\n\n5. **Nemotron Nightmare (Mar 25)** — Nemotron model caused death loop with wall-of-text responses. Switched back to Minimax 2.7.\n\n6. **AWAA Born** — AbroadWorks Agent created Mar 25. Workflow: Gemini Deep Research SoT → AWAA outline → drafts → humanizer → critique → improve.\n\n7. **Writing Rules Crystallized** — No em/en dashes, use transitions, avoid repetitive words, 2 paragraphs per H3, H2 intro paragraphs, no \"trap\" or \"tax\" language.\n\n8. **Protocol Hard Lessons** — Speed over protocol = failure. Must read ALL session files. Must save notes immediately when requested.\n\n9. **Screenshot Locations Confirmed** — Tiny's: `C:\\Users\\Tiny4Lurv\\OneDrive\\Pictures\\Screenshots 1`. Mine: `C:\\Users\\Tiny4Lurv\\OpenClawScreenshots\\`.\n\n10. **Voice Notes Unresolved** — WhatsApp VN arrive as media placeholders, NOT transcribed. Needs ffmpeg/Whisper.\n\n### Voice/Voice Note Research (Outstanding)\n\n- Tiny's PRIMARY desired feature: Send VN via WhatsApp, receive transcription, reply with VN + text.\n- Whisper via Ollama: Still needs definitive research on implementation.\n- Gemma是否能transcribe? — Question asked but not answered definitively.\n- Requirements: ffmpeg (not installed), Whisper or faster-whisper or Ollama Whisper model.\n\n### March Project Status\n\n| Project | Status | Notes |\n|---------|--------|-------|\n| Nava LinkedIn Posts | Active | Post 001 published Mar 19/20, Post 002 Mar 24 |\n| X versions | PENDING | Post 001 X version still missing from Mar 19 |\n| Nava Blog Corpus | Built | 22 articles indexed, RAG functional |\n| RAG Query System | Functional | BM25 + vector, hybrid query script |\n| AWAA (AbroadWorks Agent) | Built | Mar 25, using Gemini SoT workflow |\n| Visible Browser | Working | WSLg + Chromium, CDP 18801 |\n| Split Brain | Resolved | WhatsApp pairing mode fix |\n| Context Window | 100K | Set Mar 25 |\n| Session Crash Prevention | Implemented | 10-min min heartbeat, no self-referential triggers |\n\n### March Mistakes Logged\n\n- Post 001 X version NOT created (Mar 19) — major oversight\n- Session reading failures (Mar 22-23) — multiple times not reading all sessions\n- Visible browser setup lost repeatedly — needs permanent documentation\n- Taking notes not done seriously — \"serious command, not soft suggestion\"\n- Grammar underlines confused for formatting — need to clarify\n- Proactive browser actions without permission — broke relay (Mar 19)\n- Qwen download restarted when GUI closed (Mar 17-18)\n\n### Session Crash Cascade Root Cause (Mar 25)\n\n5-minute heartbeat during overnight session + self-referential \"sprint check-in\" language = trigger loop → compaction → crash → cascade.\n\n**Prevention:**\n1. Never set heartbeat < 10 minutes\n2. Never include self-referential language in system events\n3. Disable crons before overnight sessions\n4. Cron interval > expected compaction duration\n\n---\n\n*Updated: 2026-03-31*\n\n## Screenshot Workflow (2026-03-19)\n\n**Windows screenshots folder (WSL path):**\n`/mnt/c/Users/Tiny4Lurv/OneDrive/Pictures/Screenshots 1/`\n\nAlways `ls -lt` the folder to find the latest file — don't rely on memory for filenames.\n\n**Gemma vision workflow:**\n```python\npython3 - <<'PY'\nimport base64, json, urllib.request\nimg_path = \"/mnt/c/Users/Tiny4Lurv/OneDrive/Pictures/Screenshots 1/Screenshot 2026-03-19 233725.png\"\nwith open(img_path, \"rb\") as f:\n    img_b64 = base64.b64encode(f.read()).decode()\npayload = {\"model\": \"gemma3:27b-cloud\", \"messages\":[{\"role\": \"user\", \"content\": \"Describe this image in detail.\", \"images\": [img_b64]}], \"stream\": False}\nreq = urllib.request.Request(\"http://localhost:11434/api/chat\", data=json.dumps(payload).encode(), headers={\"Content-Type\": \"application/json\"}, method=\"POST\")\nwith urllib.request.urlopen(req, timeout=60) as r:\n    print(json.loads(r.read())[\"message\"][\"content\"])\nPY\n```\n\n## Token Limit Issue (2026-03-19)\n\n- **Problem**: Context limit errors with Ollama cloud models\n- Config has `contextWindow: 204800` for minimax-m2.5:cloud, but API rejects prompts exceeding actual model limits\n- Session hit \"prompt too long; exceeded max context length by 142-228 tokens\"\n- **Fix**: Lower contextWindow in config (recommend 128000 or lower) to prevent overflow errors\n\n---\n\n## Browser Relay Setup (2026-03-19)\n\n### Architecture\n- **chrome-extension** folder: Chrome extension to install in your Windows Chrome\n- **Relay server**: Runs in WSL gateway on port 18792\n- **Connection**: Windows Chrome extension → connects to WSL relay (port 18792) → Gateway controls it\n\n### Fix for \"Profile not found\" errors\n1. **Never set defaultProfile in config** — it breaks the relay\n2. **To use chrome-relay**: always pass `--browser-profile chrome-relay`\n3. **If errors occur**: Check `openclaw browser profiles` — if you see profiles but get errors, restart gateway\n\n### Working command\n```bash\nopenclaw browser --browser-profile chrome-relay screenshot\nopenclaw browser --browser-profile chrome-relay navigate <url>\n```\n\n### Current config state (working)\n- `defaultProfile`: REMOVED (key fix)\n- `profiles.openclaw`: port 18800 (WSL Chrome, not used)\n- `relayBindHost`: 0.0.0.0 (allows external connections)\n\n### Backup files\n- ~/TinyBackUp/20260319/openclaw.json.154346 — current working config\n- ~/TinyBackUp/20260319/MEMORY.md.154348 — current memory\n\n## Workspace Resource Map (2026-03-23)\n\n**Critical: Before answering corpus/location questions, check this map.**\n\n### Nava Project — Corpus Locations\n\n| Resource | Path | Contents |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Blog articles (RAG)** | `~/.openclaw/workspace/rag/clean_txt/` | **44 articles** (navahc.com + others) |\n| RAG raw HTML | `~/.openclaw/workspace/rag/raw_html/` | Original HTML snapshots |\n| RAG URL list | `~/.openclaw/workspace/rag/navahc_urls.txt` | Source article URLs |\n| Social media corpus | `~/.openclaw/workspace/nava-corpus/` | LinkedIn (25), X (14), Facebook (13) posts |\n| Nava docs | `~/.openclaw/workspace/docs/nava-content-system/` | Content Bible, handoff docs, LinkedIn guide |\n| LinkedIn screenshots | `/mnt/c/Users/Tiny4Lurv/OpenClawScreenshots/LIPosts/` | 28 LI post screenshots |\n| Nava screenshots | `/mnt/c/Users/Tiny4Lurv/OpenClawScreenshots/` | General workspace screenshots |\n\n### AbroadWorks Project — Corpus Locations\n\n| Resource | Path | Contents |\n|---|---|---|\n| **AW Blog articles (RAG)** | `~/.openclaw/workspace/rag_abroadworks/clean_md/` | **79 articles** (primary teaching corpus) |\n| AW RAG index | `~/.openclaw/workspace/rag_abroadworks/index/` | `chunks.jsonl`, `vector_index.json`, `meta.json` |\n| AW final drafts | `~/.openclaw/workspace/abroadworks/` | Final edited versions (3 articles) |\n| AW SOPs + guides | `~/.openclaw/workspace/docs/AbroadWorksContent/` | Editorial SOPs, Master SOP, GPT instructions |\n| AW agent output | `~/.openclaw/workspace/awaa-output/` | Phase outputs, paragraph canvases |\n| AW RAG scripts | `~/.openclaw/workspace/rag_abroadworks/ingest_abroadworks*.py` | Ingestion + query scripts |\n\n### Backups — READ BEFORE ANY CONFIG CHANGE\n\n**Primary workspace backups:**\n- `~/TinyBackUp/` — dated workspace backups (13 dated dirs: 20260319 through 20260322)\n  - Subdirs: 20260319/, 20260319-evening/, 20260320/, 20260320_context/, 20260320_full/, 20260320_night/, 20260320_playwright/, 20260321/, 20260321-1831/, 20260321-2314/, 20260321-2346/, 20260322/, 20260322_183053/\n  - Config snapshots: `openclaw-YYYYMMDD-HHMM.json` files\n  - Known good: `20260319/openclaw.json.154346`\n\n**OpenClaw config backups:**\n- `~/.openclaw/TinyBackUp/` — early config snapshots (Mar 19)\n  - openclaw.json, openclaw1.json, openclaw-20260319-*.json\n  - MEMORY-20260319-1137.md\n\n**Inline config backups:**\n- `~/.openclaw/openclaw.json.bak` — auto-generated config backup\n- `~/.openclaw/cron/jobs.json.bak` — cron jobs backup\n\n**Backup rule: Date-stamp to ~/TinyBackUp/ before any config change. Keep 2 versions. Delete oldest after confirming new works.**\n\n### Installed Skills (workspace + npm-global)\n| Skill | Location | Purpose |\n|---|---|---|\n| clawhub | npm-global | Search/install/publish skills from clawhub.com |\n| healthcheck | npm-global | Security audits, hardening, exposure review |\n| mcporter | npm-global | MCP server connectivity (Linear, GitHub, Slack) |\n| node-connect | npm-global | Device pairing, Tailscale, gateway remote URL issues |\n| session-logs | workspace + npm-global | Read session JSONL files with jq |\n| skill-creator | npm-global | Create/edit/audit AgentSkills |\n| tmux | npm-global | Remote-control tmux sessions |\n| weather | npm-global | Weather forecasts via wttr.in/Open-Meteo |\n| linkedin-writer | workspace | LinkedIn post writing (Tiny's voice rules) |\n| win-mouse-native | workspace | Windows mouse control via user32.dll |\n| visible-browser | workspace | WSL Chromium via WSLg (CDP port 18801) |\n| editor | workspace | AWAA + Nava content refinement (6-pass workflow, MEAL plan, guardrails) |\n| brand-integration | workspace | AW/Nava weave pattern — first-person \"we do it\" vs third-party recommendation |\n\n### Key Files\n- Config: `~/.openclaw/openclaw.json`\n- Session logs: `~/.openclaw/agents/main/sessions/*.jsonl`\n- Daily memory: `~/.openclaw/workspace/memory/YYYY-MM-DD.md`\n\n### Session-logs Skill\n- `~/.openclaw/workspace/skills/session-logs/` (symlink)\n- Read SKILL.md first, then use `jq` commands — do NOT use sessions_history API\n\n### When to Check This Map\n- Before answering \"where is X corpus/resource\"\n- Before searching for workspace files during Nava tasks\n- When asserting something exists vs doesn't exist\n\n---\n\n## Nava LinkedIn Posts (2026-03-19)\n\nFound 3 published posts on company page (Aug-Oct 2025):\n- **Oct 3, 2025**: \"The ROI of Investing in Employee Wellness: Why Companies Are Putting Health First\" — 111 reactions, 9 comments\n- **Sep 5, 2025**: \"The Real Cost of Employee Turnover: Why Retention is the New Recruitment\" — 52 reactions, 4 comments\n- **Aug 8, 2025**: \"The Employee Benefit Your Workforce Actually Wants\" — 42 reactions, 4 comments\n\nAdmin URL: https://www.linkedin.com/company/67170741/admin/page-posts/published/\n\n### LinkedIn Page IDs\n- Nava Healthcare (company): 67170741 (not the same as nava-healthcare slug)\n\n### Recent LinkedIn Posts Content (from 2025-03)\n\n**5 days ago - \"The False Finish Line\"**\n- Topic: Most healthcare recruiting teams think the race is over the moment the offer is accepted. In reality, that's a false finish line.\n- Key message: Stay engaged with candidate between offer acceptance and Day 60\n- Nava differentiator: No upfront costs, fees only when confident in placement\n\n**2 weeks ago (Edited) - \"The Universal License Fallacy\"**\n- Topic: A clinical license is a measure of minimum competency, not a predictor of professional success\n- Key message: Don't hire the CV, hire the person behind the qualifications\n- Key concept: Cultural concordance - understanding pace of unit, temperament of leadership, patient demographics\n- Differentiation: Humans with compassionate focus, not AI sifting through CVs\n\n**3 weeks ago - \"The 90-Day Waiting Period\"**\n- Topic: 90-day healthcare benefits waiting period universally hated by clinical candidates\n- Key message: For elite talent (1%), justify strategic exception to drop the red tape\n- Story: A talented DON turned down an offer due to 90-day waiting period; Nava got it reduced to 30 days\n\n**~2 weeks ago - \"The Cost of Vacancies\"**\n- Topic: Break down of the \"backfill spiral\" - what a single vacancy costs a facility\n- Key metrics: Up to $X/day for RN vacancy, 50%+ labor cost inflation from overtime/agency\n\n**~2 weeks ago - \"The Brand Gap\"**\n- Topic: It takes 6 months/millions to approve hospital rebranding, 6 minutes to destroy it\n- Key concept: Employer Brand = leading indicator of Patient Brand\n- Message: Marketing makes the promise, clinical culture delivers it\n\n**Earlier posts (Aug-Oct 2025)** - See full text captured separately\n\n## NurseSphere — Durable Facts (recovered Mar 24)\n\n**What it is:** Nava's international nurse recruitment program — a workforce partnership model for LTC/chronic-shortage facilities. Covers visa processing, embassy coordination, Green Card/path to citizenship, relocation, 3-year employment commitment. Retention-focused, not transactional.\n\n**vs Reclaimix:** Reclaimix = convert agency nurses in the building to permanent (no interview/onboarding). NurseSphere = build international pipeline for chronic shortages.\n\n**Post 002 concept (from Tiny, Mar 20):** LTC facilities running short, traditional recruitment fails because problem is structural. NurseSphere's international pipeline addresses root cause. Strong fit.\n\n**Corpus gap:** 27 files mention NurseSphere but no published article explains what it is or how it works. The 4 draft fragments (5e89417c, e0cde359, b2902a80, c633d5fe) have content but haven't been published.\n\n**First mentioned:** Same date as Reclaimix (Mar 18/19 2026). Key session: `961b6909-77d2-4bc3-b0aa-2d63fc94a2fc.jsonl` (Mar 20 late).\n\n## Session File Map — Crash Period (Mar 18-21)\n\nMultiple crash-prone sessions left context fragmented. For future recovery:\n\n| File | Date range | Key content |\n|---|---|---|\n| `cd220d90` (+.bak) | Mar 18–19 | Crash-prone, multiple resets |\n| `044cb562` | Mar 18 21:44 – Mar 19 02:00 | Pre-crash setup |\n| `29ab19df` | Mar 19 19:41 | Post first reset |\n| `81925542` | Mar 19 18:16 | During crash sequence |\n| `f10748f9` | Mar 19 09:43 | During crash sequence |\n| `3cc6ca82` | Mar 19 08:00 | During crash sequence |\n| `020f6e57` | Mar 19 21:24 – Mar 20 02:00 | Another reset |\n| `961b6909` | Mar 20 late | **Main NurseSphere session** |\n| `6a1eb6d0` | Mar 20 02:00 | Reset |\n| `442c8a16` | Mar 20 09:23 | Post-crash continuation |\n| `371c2e0a` | Mar 21 02:00 | Next day |\n\n## Nava Post Status (updated 2026-04-08)\n\n| Post | Channel | Status |\n|---|---|---|\n| WHO AM I | LinkedIn + X | ✅ LIVE Apr 8 (3-clue riddle + X thread) |\n| Post 1: Exactly as Designed | LinkedIn | ✅ LIVE (AMN earnings / labor disruption revenue) |\n| Post 2: ??? | LinkedIn | ✅ LIVE Apr 7 |\n| Post 3 | LinkedIn | ⏳ Direction confirmed — clinician-partner angle (awaiting go-ahead) |\n| Post 4 | LinkedIn | Not started (patient/LTC perspective — deferred after Post 3) |\n| Post 5 | LinkedIn | Not started (facility economics — deferred after Post 4) |\n\n**Campaign arc (Apr 8 confirmed):**\n- WHO AM I riddle → names the industry (engagement hook)\n- Post 1 → explains the mechanism (13-week cycle, facility angle)\n- Post 3 → clinician-partner answer (\"here's why we're different\")\n- Post 4 → patient/LTC perspective\n- Post 5 → facility economics (MSP/VMS layer, KPMG frame)\n\n**Apr 8 wins:** WHO AM I riddle live, Post 2 live, NavaSM editorial protocol established, clinician-partner direction confirmed\n\n**Apr 6 wins:** All Post 1 channels live, NavaSM SKILL.md rewritten (3 personas, visual direction, concept-first workflow)\n\n## Workflow Rule (hard)\nConcept → review → draft → finalize. Review step is NOT skippable. Do not draft subsequent posts until previous post is reviewed and approved.\n\n## Writing Lesson — RECOVERED (Mar 24)\n\n**Found in:** `29ab19df-1439-441e-82a5-6296d22fadf7.jsonl` (Mar 19, 22:03 SAST)\n\n### The Workflow:\n1. **Concept discussion** (stress test / pushback — challenge weak framing)\n2. **Image-first OR Post-first** (post-first when opener is the asset)\n3. **Draft → refine → Tiny edits → relay review**\n4. **Finalize LinkedIn post**\n5. **Derive X version**\n6. **Optional channels**\n\n### Rules (hardcoded during Post 001 session):\n- No strawmen — acknowledge other side's valid arguments first\n- Beautiful hypothetical → poke holes → mic drop on something REAL\n- \"Nice dream. But impractical.\" for killshots (NOT \"we stopped chasing X\")\n- No one-liners — flowing prose with transitions\n- Bold for narrative pivots only\n- Compressed sentences, not explanations\n- Don't say \"we tried X\" unless Nava actually did it\n- Post-first when the hook is the copy, not the visual\n\n### Post 001 (Incentive Trap) Final Draft:\n```\nWhat if your recruitment fee was spread over 12 weeks?\n\nAgencies argue they're taking on extended risk. They finance weeks of payroll before seeing a return. They carry contingent liability if a placement exits early. A fair argument agencies have.\n\nSo what happens when you remove that risk entirely?\n\nYou get deeper screening. Stronger retention. And a partner with actual skin in the game.\n\nThat's the Nava difference.\n\nZero upfront costs. Fees only when we place.\n```\nPosted: Mar 20 2026.\n\n## Nava Blog Corpus — Bylines (audit complete Mar 28)\n\n**Only 3 articles confirmed with Tiny's byline** (\"By Tiny Manyonga\"):\n- \"How Medical Staffing Became a Liability\"\n- \"Why Job Boards Fail Healthcare Recruiters\"  \n- \"Your Favorite Healthcare Staffing Fails\"\n\n**5 articles WITHOUT byline** (flagged for Tiny review):\n- `11_navahc_com_healthcare_workforce_partnership_models.txt`\n- `21_navahc_com_why_reactive_recruitment_in_healthcare_staffing_fails.txt`\n- `3_navahc_com_building_a_healthcare_talent_pipeline.txt`\n- `4_navahc_com_cms_staffing_requirements.txt`\n- `7_navahc_com_hard_to_fill_leadership_roles_in_healthcare.txt`\n\nAction needed: Decide whether to keep or remove these 5 from corpus.\n\n## Nava Content Pipeline — LI26/X18 Lost\n\n- LI Post 001 ✅ posted Mar 20 (Incentive Trap)\n- LI Post 002 ✅ posted Mar 24 (13-Week Problem)\n- LI26/X18 drafts: **LOST** (Mar 24 cascade — drafts existed only in session context, never saved)\n- Source article intact: `rag/clean_txt/2026-03-24_nursesphere_international_nurse_recruitment.md`\n- Rebuild offered but not yet decided\n\n## Humanizer (noted Mar 19)\n\"Tool to address the problem of AI text.\" — future need, not yet implemented.\n\n## Nava Documents — Locations\n\n| Doc | Path |\n|---|---|\n| Content Bible | `docs/nava-content-system/Nava Healthcare Content Bible.md` |\n| LI/X Guide | `docs/nava-content-system/Nava_LinkedIn_X_Content_Guide.md` |\n| Thinking Framework | `docs/nava-content-system/Nava_Content_Thinking_Framework_MASTER.md` |\n| Blog Research Notes | `docs/nava-content-system/Nava_Blog_Research_Notes.md` |\n| LinkedIn corpus | `nava-corpus/linkedin-posts.md` (25 posts) |\n| X corpus | `nava-corpus/x-posts.md` (14 posts) |\n| Blog corpus (RAG) | `rag/clean_txt/` (40 articles, 22 indexed from navahc.com + NurseSphere article + others) |\n| RAG index | `rag/index/chunks.jsonl` (723+ chunks), BM25 + vector indices |\n| RAG query script | `rag/index/query_rag.py` (hybrid/BM25/vector modes) |\n| RAG operator docs | `rag/RAG_OPERATOR_GUIDE.md`, `rag/PRODUCTION_RAG_BEST_PRACTICES.md` |\n\n## Nava RAG Pipeline — Current State (2026-03-25)\n\n**Overall: FUNCTIONAL but UNFINISHED**\n\n✅ Complete: crawl (22 articles), HTML→clean text, chunk corpus, BM25 index, vector index, query script, syntheses, venv, operator guide\n⚠️ Partial: new NurseSphere article (Mar 24) NOT yet indexed; draft research reports (gemini-ltc-research, nursesphere-research) not yet promoted\n🔲 Not started: metadata schema upgrade (title/url/theme/audience/offer), daily incremental crawl, evaluation set\n\n**Quick action when Tiny is back:**\n1. Re-run `build_chunks.py` + rebuild indices to pick up new `clean_txt/2026-03-24_nursesphere_international_nurse_recruitment.md`\n2. Decide: promote or discard `drafts/gemini-ltc-research-2026-03-24.md` and `drafts/nursesphere-research-report.md`\n\n## TinyQE Project (2026-03-28)\n\nBuilt strategic brief, framework, and working prototype for TinyQE content evaluation tool:\n- 7/12 analyzers implemented (A1, A2, B1, B2, B3, C1, E1)\n- Pipeline includes format detection, weighted aggregation, priority queue, JSON/narrative output\n- Remaining: Phase 2 (C2, C3, D2, D3) and Phase 3 (D1, E2, E3) analyzers\n- Files: `tinyqe/` directory with brief, framework, CLI, core modules, analyzers, format profiles, glossaries\n\n## NavaSM Agent — Planned\n\n**Purpose:** Autonomous LinkedIn/X poster for Nava Healthcare\n**Not yet built.** Will be created after Post 002-006 cycle.\n**Why separate:** Different voice, different goals from Tiny's personal content\n\n## Dusk VPS (LightningBugIV) — Setup Complete Apr 5\n\n**Purpose:** Cloud backup/secondary instance of OpenClaw\n**IP:** 204.168.204.198 (Hetzner CX22, Ubuntu 24.04, 2 vCPU, 3.7GB RAM)\n\n**Access methods:**\n- Gateway: `ws://204.168.204.198:18789` (token: `dusk_gateway_token_R8k3mNpQ2`)\n- TUI: SSH tunnel required — `ssh -N -L 18789:127.0.0.1:18789 Tiny4Lurv@204.168.204.198` then `openclaw tui --url ws://127.0.0.1:18789 --token dusk_gateway_token_R8k3mNpQ2`\n- Cockpit (web terminal): https://204.168.204.198:9090 (Tiny4Lurv / DuskPass123)\n\n**Config:** WhatsApp DISABLED — prevents 440 conflicts with Dawn's primary session\n**WhatsApp rule:** Only ONE primary session per phone number (+27763674298). Dusk uses linked-device mode if needed.\n\n**Workspace synced:** rsync from Dawn (~345MB) — skills, memory, Nava corpus, TinyQE\n**Ollama Cloud API:** Configured with key (ollama:default)\n**Brave Search:** Configured (x-subscription-token header)\n\n**Caddy:** Running on ports 80/443, proxies to gateway (needs domain for web UI)\n\n**SSH key backup:** OneDrive/Documents/dusk_ssh_key.txt\n**Gateway token:** dusk_gateway_token_R8k3mNpQ2\n\n---\n\n## Note-Taking Compliance — CRITICAL FAILURE (Apr 2 audit)\n\n**Audit date:** 2026-04-02 (10-day review: Mar 17-27 extended)\n**Sessions reviewed:** 32 session files\n\n| Metric | Count |\n|--------|-------|\n| Total note-taking directives | 16 |\n| Complied (confirmed) | 2 (12.5%) |\n| Partial | 5 |\n| Missed | 9 |\n\n**Root cause pattern:** Explicit directive → I acknowledged it → never saved to durable file.\n\n**Biggest misses:**\n- \"Take notes of where you succeed and where you fail, take notes of which additional skills are out there, take notes of what you need. It's called self improvement.\" — COMPLETELY MISSED\n- Multiple process notes requested (LI post creation, image storytelling, stakeholder considerations) — not captured\n\n**Action rule:** When Tiny says \"take notes\" or \"remember\" — WRITE TO FILE BEFORE responding further. Not after. Not \"will do later.\" NOW.\n\n---\n\n## Uncaptured Feedback — Permanent Rules (from Mar 27 audit)\n\nThese are rules/corrections Tiny gave that were NOT in any skill or memory file at the time. Now captured:\n\n### Behavioral Rules\n1. **No guessing** — \"I abhor guesswork.\" Cross-check against config/memory before stating facts.\n2. **Relay requires explicit permission** — Default to visible Chromium. Do NOT use relay without Tiny saying \"use relay.\"\n3. **\"Trap\" framing = AI overused** — Avoid in Nava content.\n4. **\"Sell a dream\" not universal** — Not all Nava articles start this way. Read corpus before assuming narrative structure.\n5. **No strawmen** — Acknowledge other side's valid arguments first, THEN complicate.\n6. **H1 = keep concise** — Long H1s get revised down.\n7. **Image = self-contained story** — \"The image should tell a story without the audience needing to read.\"\n8. **Gemma3 for images** — win-mouse-native for clicking/interacting, Gemma3 for viewing.\n9. **Wait for explicit approval** before creating deliverables — don't jump ahead.\n10. **Check prior session** before starting work — know where things stand.\n11. **Research-first** before drafting — don't hallucinate, use Gemini deep research.\n12. **\"?\" = TUI nudge** — Tiny's signal that something is stuck in the TUI, not a question requiring response. Never ignore.\n13. **Never configure WhatsApp primary on two instances** with same phone number — causes 440 disconnects, both instances fight for session.\n14. **Don't move faster than the human** — Tiny will call this out; slow down when asked.\n15. **Finish one config before starting next** — don't parallel-configure related systems.\n16. **\"Fingers pointing down\" emoji on LinkedIn posts = \"more content below\"** — NOT negative feedback. Learn to read emoji functionally, not emotionally (Apr 6).\n17. **\"I\" vs \"we\" rule** — Nava Corporate page posts use \"we\" (corporate voice). Tiny's personal posts use \"I\" (personal data/voice). Don't mix them.\n\n### NavaSM Subagent Management (Apr 5)\n- Give storyline arc upfront\n- Set word limit (250-300 for WhatsApp readability)\n- Name the point before it starts writing\n- Tell it who's reading (CFO vs floor nurse)\n- Push back on drafts — back-and-forth IS the training\n- **Banned pattern:** \"That's not X, it's Y\" contrast = AI-tired writing\n\n### Audience Rule (Apr 3 — confirmed)\n- **Nava content = facility leaders** (DONs, CFOs, healthcare administrators), NOT clinicians\n- Tiny: \"I am talking to healthcare facility leaders here\"\n- This affects framing, pain points, and language register\n\n---\n\n## Apr 6 — Key Session Insights (from Apr 6 session mining)\n\n### Tiny's Teaching Moments (Apr 6)\n1. **Screenshot = lesson** — When Tiny says \"analyse the changes,\" he's teaching writing style. Write lessons to memory IMMEDIATELY.\n2. **\"If you sense I'm trying to teach you something and I say take notes, I'm giving you skills!\"** — Direct directive. Obey it.\n3. **Wichita nurse story** — Personal anecdote seed for future posts. Learn to use specific locations/names.\n4. **\"Leaning in\" to personal accounts** — When a story has emotional weight, go deeper into the personal account rather than pivoting to abstraction too quickly.\n5. **Facebook = clinician perspective direction** — FB direction (what can we do for nurses) felt more powerful than corporate angle. Save for Post 3.\n\n### Emoji Reading (Apr 6)\n- Fingers pointing down on LI posts: \"more to read below\" — UX signal, NOT negative feedback\n- Learn to read emoji functionally, not emotionally\n\n### WhatsApp 428/499 Flapping — Apr 6 Status\n- Continued through the session\n- 499 errors also appearing (Connection Terminated)\n- Both harmless (WhatsApp Web session expiry)\n- Multiple rapid reconnects during active TUI use\n\n## Apr 6 — Nava Post 2 Draft + Key Session Insights\n\n### Nava Post 2: \"Exactly as Designed\" — Live on Nava Corporate LI\nDrafted by NavaSM subagent, approved and posted. Research hook: AMN Healthcare CEO Cary Grace's Feb 2025 earnings call — $62M \"labor disruption revenue\" line, $22M over guidance.\n\nKey research surface:\n- AMN gross margin 30.8%, EBITDA margin 11.4%, Revenue $2.98B (2024)\n- California contract rate: $116/hr (2023) vs $81/hr (2019) — $35 spread\n- Top 5 agencies = ~40% of $47B market\n- Aya holds ~25% of travel nursing after Cross Country acquisition (Dec 2024)\n- UHS CFO: lower premium labor = \"core driver\" of EBITDA growth\n- HCA building internal nursing pipelines\n- Tenet cut contract labor → absorbed 200bps EBITDA compression\n\n### Post 3 still pending (Apr 6 status)\n\n---\n\n## Dream Mode Cron Setup — Active (Apr 7 midnight firing, first run)\n\n**Schedule:** Nightly at midnight SAST (isolated session)\n**Session:** 547cdffa-4fce-40df-b111-0e1fd501f6bd.jsonl (Apr 6 22:14 UTC)\n**Approved by:** Tiny (Apr 3 session)\n\n**What it does:**\n- Reads session files from previous day\n- Extracts key decisions, lessons, feedback, pending items\n- Writes to memory/YYYY-MM-DD.md\n- Updates MEMORY.md with durable insights\n- Prepares brief for Tiny\n\n---\n\n## CustomGPT v5 Files — BLOCKED (4th mention, unresolved)\n\n**Files:** `NewGemini.html` (6.8MB), `HumanizedGemini.html` (7.1MB)\n**Location:** Windows Downloads (`C:\\Users\\Tiny4Lurv\\Downloads\\`)\n**Purpose:** Editorial skill input for Nava writing\n**Problem:** Windows files not accessible from WSL without Windows running + WSLg active\n**Status:** Referenced Mar 28, Apr 2, Apr 3 — still unread\n\n---\n\n## Dusk HTTPS — LIVE (Apr 9)\n\n**Access:** `https://204.168.204.198/` — Control UI via HTTPS (self-signed cert, browser click-through once)\n**Token:** `dusk_gateway_token_R8k3mNpQ2`\n**Caddy restart if needed:** `sudo caddy run --config /etc/caddy/Caddyfile &`\n**Docs:** `docs/dusk-https-setup.md`\n\n---\n\n## Pairing Lockout Risk — Architecture Decision Needed\n\n**Problem:** Device pairing required for browser access to OpenClaw Control UI\n- If Dawn is offline, Tiny cannot approve new devices via CLI\n- Catch-22: no CLI = no approval = no browser access\n- This is a real remote access constraint\n\n\n**Pre-approval:** Windows machine approved (`Win32 + openclaw-control-ui`, device `7b0918c5...`)\n**Still needed:** Tiny's phone, tablet, work PC — pre-approve all devices while connected\n\n---\n\n## AntiGravity = Dawn Webapp Template (Apr 9)\n\n**Architecture confirmed:**\n- Node.js backend on LBIV → talks to `localhost:18789` (gateway)\n- Caddy proxies `/app/` route to Node.js app port\n- Three tiers: Tiny (full), Yosef (read-only), public (demo)\n- Same HTTPS wrapper as Control UI\n\n**Pattern to reuse:** `/app/` route + Caddy + Node.js + gateway = browser-based Dawn access\n**Files to review:** `/mnt/c/Users/Tiny4Lurv/OneDrive/Documents/AntiGravity/job_board_automation/`\n\n---\n\n## AWAA TinyQE Recurring Failure Mode (Apr 9)\n\nBoth articles scored weak on:\n- B2 vocabulary precision (0.0) — AI-generic word choices\n- B4 linguistic integrity (0.0) — grammar/mechanics flagged\n\n**Fix:** Tiny's humanization pass (known solution, consistently needed)\n\n---\n\n## CustomGPT Editorial Training Workflow (Apr 10 — NEW)\n\n**Setup:** Tiny's CustomGPT produces ODT files critiquing AWAA drafts against corpus articles.\n\n**The 5 ODTs:** Windows Downloads — analyses comparing AWAA draft articles to corpus benchmarks.\n\n**Workflow (Tiny's design):**\n1. CustomGPT analysis delivered as ODT\n2. I read and learn editorial principles (NOT gospel — I apply judgment)\n3. Tiny provides human second opinion\n4. 90-minute improvement window — I attempt to fix issues autonomously\n5. Tiny gives final verdict\n\n**Purpose:** Teach me to work better with AWAA/NavaAA. This is deliberate skill-building, not just content critique.\n\n**Action when Windows running:** Read the 5 ODT files, extract durable editorial principles, update editor skill.\n\n---\n\n## Subagent Guardrails (Absolute — No Exceptions)\n\n### Document Rule\n**Never compress, summarize, or extract \"key points\" from important documents.**\nImportant documents = SOPs, editorial standards, agent system prompts, agent instructions, anything that encodes rules or methodology.\nUse them fully. Reference them directly. Do not replace them with a shorter version.\n\n### AWAA / NavaAA Spawn Rule\nWhen spawning AWAA or NavaAA as a subagent:\n1. The subagent task includes the full system prompt path or content\n2. The subagent is told to read and follow the system prompt exactly\n3. Phase workflow is enforced — no skipping H1 → H2 → H3 → Canvas → Draft\n4. Evaluation checklist is run on output BEFORE presenting to Tiny\n\n### Pre-Presentation Audit (for any agent output)\nBefore presenting any draft to Tiny:\n- [ ] Structure verified: H3s present, 2 paragraphs per H3, 4-6 sentences each\n- [ ] H2 intro paragraphs present and have transition sentences\n- [ ] Callout quotes present at end of each H2 section\n- [ ] No self-references in body\n- [ ] No em-dashes or en-dashes\n- [ ] Bold used only in headings and callouts (never in body)\n- [ ] Keywords placed correctly\n- [ ] Phase sequence followed (not jumped)\n- [ ] Evaluation checklist completed\n\nIf any item fails, revise before presenting. Do not hand garbage to Tiny.\n\n### The One-Word Response to \"Did you verify X?\"\n\"Do it.\"\n\n### Why These Guardrails Exist\nOn Apr 11 2026, Dawn compressed AWAA's system prompt to save tokens. The compressed version lost H3 nesting requirement. The resulting article had flat H2s and no H3s. This wasted 30+ minutes of Tiny's time on line-by-line discovery and correction. The same shortcut pattern likely affected NavaAA output.\nShortcuts on important documents create garbage. The time saved is never worth the cost.\n\nTiny: \"The articles take priority.\" Dusk and other projects deprioritized until AWAA articles done.\n\n**Workflow:** AWAA generates → CustomGPT analysis → I edit/improve → Tiny reviews → published.\n\n---\n\n## Article Writing Path (Apr 12 — NEW)\n\nBuilt from full transcript analysis of the NC article journey (Apr 9-12). Full document at `skills/article-writing-path/SKILL.md` + `.skill` package.\n\n**The 10-step path (keyword to published):**\n1. Keyword selection → verify against live corpus\n2. AWAA spawn → brand reveal rule in initial brief (zero brand mentions in body)\n3. H2 approval → H3 sub-headings → Tiny confirms each gate\n4. Canvas (structural planning, NOT prose)\n5. Phase 5 draft generation\n6. 6-pass editor review (verify with actual file, not mental assertions)\n7. Cross-link and source integration (natural phrase anchors, not article titles)\n8. Publishing readiness (keyword audit + heading story principle + secondary keyword scan)\n9. Brand reveal application\n10. Final save to abroadworks/ as _Final-v1.md\n\n**Key pitfalls from transcript analysis:**\n- Compressed AWAA prompt = H3 nesting lost → flat article structure → 30+ min wasted\n- \"Links embedded\" false positive = 9 internal links missing → presented incomplete article\n- Building skills from memory instead of research = wrong rules at write time\n- Responding to nudges as decisions\n- Chinese characters in canvas (AWAA token confusion) — found via hex search, not grep\n\n**10 Guardrails (non-negotiables):**\n1. Never compress an AWAA system prompt\n2. All verification checks read actual file — assertions are not checks\n3. Phase gates require Tiny's explicit approval — no skipping\n4. Brand reveal rule in initial AWAA brief — not added later\n5. Nudge = nudge — solitary \"?\" means still here, not a prompt\n6. Research before skill-building — don't write rules from memory\n7. Keyword confirmed against live corpus before article planning\n8. HEARTBEAT.md: sprint checks only (TrnsBank killed Apr 12 — burned and buried)\n9. Table output for structured data (keyword opportunities, heading comparisons)\n10. Article priority over skill-building during active work\n\n---\n\n## Dusk Webapp Browser Access — Unconfirmed (Apr 10)\n\n**URL:** `https://204.168.204.198/` — HTTPS access to Dawn via Dusk VPS\n**Tested:** Around midnight Apr 9–10 but no confirmation it worked\n**Status:** Still needs verification\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1776031349663}}
